  "topic": "Linux Security and Firewall",
  "slides": [
    {
      "slideId": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Introduction to Linux Security"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "Linux security protects the system from unauthorized access, misuse, or damage by controlling permissions, users, and network access."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Linux provides multiple layers of security: user permissions, sudo for admin control, firewall rules for network protection, and SELinux for system policy enforcement."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Security Component", "Purpose"],
            ["sudo", "Run admin commands safely without logging in as root"],
            ["ufw/firewalld", "Firewall to control allowed/blocked network traffic"],
            ["SELinux", "Advanced security policy enforcement (mandatory access control)"],
            ["Permissions (rwx)", "Controls who can read/write/execute files"],
            ["Ownership", "Determines which user/group controls the file"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Security rule: Never work as root full-time. Use sudo only when required."
        }
      ]
    },



    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Using sudo for Secure Privileged Access"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "sudo allows a normal user to run admin commands with permission, instead of logging in as root. This reduces security risks and logs actions."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo apt update",
          "description": "Run system updates using admin privileges."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo usermod -aG sudo student",
          "description": "Add a user to sudo group (grant admin access)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo visudo",
          "description": "Safely edit sudo permissions configuration file."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "visudo prevents mistakes that could lock you out of admin access."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/shorts/ET9HA2fv6rM"
      }
    },



    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Firewall Basics (ufw & firewalld)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Firewalls control which incoming/outgoing connections are allowed. They block suspicious access and protect services."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo ufw enable",
          "description": "Enable firewall (Ubuntu/Debian)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo ufw allow 22",
          "description": "Allow SSH on port 22."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo ufw status",
          "description": "Check allowed services and ports."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent",
          "description": "Allow HTTP service (CentOS/RHEL)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo firewall-cmd --reload",
          "description": "Apply firewall rule changes."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Only open the ports you actually need: SSH, HTTP, HTTPS, Database, etc."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/shorts/u8ePspcaeyo"
      }
    },



    {
      "slideId": 4,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Intro to SELinux (Security-Enhanced Linux)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "SELinux enforces security policies system-wide. It controls which programs can access which files, even if permissions seem correct."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Mode", "Meaning"],
            ["Enforcing", "SELinux blocks unauthorized actions (recommended)"],
            ["Permissive", "Logs warnings but does not block"],
            ["Disabled", "Turns off SELinux (not recommended)"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sestatus",
          "description": "Check if SELinux is running."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo setenforce 0   # Permissive\nsudo setenforce 1   # Enforcing",
          "description": "Temporarily change SELinux mode."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "If a service fails but permissions look fine â†’ SELinux might be blocking it."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
